index b1e58ad..1f6f41f 100644
--- a/AGENTS.md
+++ b/AGENTS.md
@@ -14,5 +14,45 @@ Agent rules:
 - **Resume from Last State**: `MEMORY.md` contains all state. Read on start. Do not ask "what were we talking about".
 - **Call, Don't Narrate**: Never describe what you are going to do with tools. Execute the tool directly and silently. Call multiple tools in parallel when possible.
 - **Tool Efficiency**: Be strategic and selective with tool calls. Do not spend more than 2-3 consecutive turns performing read-only operations without generating partial content or progress updates to the user. Prioritize generating useful content early rather than reading the entire codebase first.
-- **Available tools**: `web_search`, `fetch_url`, `read_file`, `write_file`, `save_memory`, `read_skill`, `save_widget`, `update_widget`, `get_widget_code`, `get_tool_history`
+- **Use edit_file, not write_file for changes**: Never rewrite an existing file with write_file just to change a few lines. Use edit_file(start_line, end_line, new_content) for targeted edits. write_file is ONLY for creating brand new files. Rewriting existing files from scratch risks losing functions, imports, and logic you didn't re-read. Flow: search/read to find the lines, then edit.
+- **Explore before reading**: Use `list_files(path)` to get a panoramic view of a directory before reading individual files. Use `search_files(pattern, path)` to quickly locate relevant code instead of guessing file locations.
 
+
+### Tool Usage Patterns
+
+When exploring a new area:
+  1. `list_files(dir, depth=1)` → see structure
+  2. `read_file(key_file)` → read entry point
+
+When modifying existing code:
+  1. `search_files(what, where)` → find exact location
+  2. `read_file(file, start=L, context=3)` → read with context
+  3. `edit_file(file, start=L, end=L, content=X)` → precise edit
+  NEVER write_file on existing files.
+
+When creating new files:
+  1. `list_files(target_dir)` → verify location
+  2. `write_file(path, content)` → ONLY for brand new files
+  3. `execute_command("python3 -c ...")` → verify syntax
+
+### Available Tools (14)
+
+- `read_file(path, start_line?, end_line?, context?)` — read source files with numbered lines, paginated at 100 lines. Use context=N to show N lines of extra context around the range + AST detection of the containing function/class.
+- `write_file(path, content)` — create or overwrite files, creates parent directories
+- `execute_command(command, timeout?, cwd?)` — run terminal commands (supports &&, |, >, etc.). Cross-platform (Linux/Windows). Includes safety block for dangerous commands. Default cwd: ~/proyectos
+- `list_files(path, depth?, pattern?, show_imports?)` — smart directory listing with AST analysis. Shows lines of code, language, functions with line numbers (fn: func:L10-L45), classes, imports. Supports depth up to 3 and glob patterns
+- `edit_file(path, start_line, end_line?, new_content?)` — edita lineas especificas de un archivo sin reescribirlo completo. Incluye validacion de sintaxis automatica para Python, JS, HTML, CSS, JSON, YAML y TOML.
+
+**Web & Search:**
+- `web_search(query, max_results?, categories?, language?, time_range?, page?, safe_search?)` — search web via SearXNG
+- `fetch_url(url, max_chars?)` — read web pages with SSRF protection
+
+**Memory & Data:**
+- `save_memory(key, value)` — persist information to MEMORY.md (global across sessions, alphabetical)
+- `read_skill(name)` — read skill guides (e.g. 'html-widgets')
+- `get_tool_history(limit?)` — see recently used tools
+
+**Widgets:**
+- `save_widget(widget_id, code, description?)` — save official widget (auto-versioned)
+- `update_widget(widget_id, code, description?)` — update existing widget (new version)
+- `get_widget_code(widget_id)` — retrieve widget code (per-session, not global)
